The above observations prompt us to formulate a method that can approximately evaluate the average heat flux on the cylinder, or the total heat flow from the cylinder. Suppose that we have a given condition for the incoming groundwater velocity, and that the cylinder is completely submerged. If this is the case, the average Nusselt number is given by Nu¯=1.015Pe1/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\overline{{{\text{Nu}}}} = 1.015{\text{Pe}}^{1/2}$$\end{document}. If the cylinder is partially submerged, the first approximation is to neglect the heat flow on the cylinder wall contacting with the upper dry layer, compared with the heat flow on the lower wet layer, as seen in Fig. 11. That is to say, the heat flow takes place only on the portion where the cylinder wall is contacting with the water-saturated lower layer. In doing so, we first define the fraction of the arc length, s, over the total peripheral length,8ψ=sπd.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\psi = \frac{s}{\pi d}.$$\end{document}

In order to compute the average heat flux, we simply multiply the average heat flux from the completely submerged case with the fraction ψ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\psi$$\end{document} defined by Eq. (8), i.e., 9q″¯=h¯Th-T0ψ=1.015keffdPe1/2Th-T0ψ.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\overline{{q^{\prime \prime } }} = \overline{h}\left( {T_{h} - T_{0} } \right)\psi = 1.015\frac{{k_{{{\text{eff}}}} }}{d}{\text{Pe}}^{1/2} \left( {T_{h} - T_{0} } \right)\psi .$$\end{document}

